The four load balancer types.

There are four, and three are current. The application load balancer works at layer seven; it understands web traffic and routes on content like path, host, header, or query, which makes it right for web apps, ay-pee-eyes, and microservices.

The network load balancer works at layer four; it moves t-c-p and u-d-p connections without parsing them, gives you a static address per zone, and handles millions of requests per second at very low latency, which suits real-time, gaming, and financial workloads, or anything needing a fixed address.

The gateway load balancer works at layer three and transparently passes traffic through third-party network appliances like firewalls. And the classic load balancer is the legacy option, kept only for old migrations.

For anything new, use the application load balancer for web traffic and the network load balancer for everything else.
